</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/udiako.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Diako</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(5/28/02 9:38:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2494.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kitting, and things Druid need to realize...</span><hr size=1> I agree Digilos on the quadding, where I try to get some mobs... then find out it's been cleaned up by 2 druid quadding.  Then I go Doh!<br>
<br>
Personally, it's a chase for the mob.  They got to it first, so I can't really bitch.  It does screw up my pulls, but I don't have to stay...  Instead of being told to leave, or hear something sarcastic/nasty I tend to keep my mouth shot.  Unless i get killed, which then... I'm a bit passed irritated.   hehe<br>
<br>
I don't hate Druids, and I played a wizard to 54 on Sullon Zek.  As a wizard... I Quad (well, only 3) rockhopper a lot in Danshroud.  Then again, I was alone almost all the time cause the server is so low on population...  and also a very dangerous zone for PVP, cause Evil/Newts loved to come and kill those at Rockhopper while we were busy.   Ah....  I don't miss the paranoia anymore  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Had a Druid Buff both my chars like 20 min after the incident that killed my Cleric.  I was so greatfull, and I know that there are as many Good Druids as there are Poor ones.  I finally understand now why people bitch at the Druids that say they didn't do anything wrong...  Mostly when the Druids say &quot;You must have done something&quot;... which is totally false, and lack of knowledge in their own class.  You're too far, mob will go for a better target if it crosses one.  Low hp/Complete Heal, or just plain KOS targets.   Accident happens.  It sucks, but it's part of life.   But to do it 4-5 times within an hour, killing 2+ people in an area... shows no respect for others.  All I know is that this Druid left after I said something in OOc... that stopped the kitting from him/her. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/udarkomen42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DarkOmen42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I had the 15k post on R&R<br>and all I got was this<br>lousy title!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(5/28/02 10:45:02 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2494.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kitting, and things Druid need to realize...</span><hr size=1> Quadding and taking up spawns isn't really the real problem though, unless the druid or wizard has KEI or C2 they are going to take a while to med up. <p>[55 Blackguard] <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=96718" title="Magelo profile">Harabakc Taintedblade</a> (Dwarf)
<a href="http://www.oboo.org" title="www.OBOO.org" >Bears of Oboo</a><br>

[52 Wanderer] <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=96724" title="Magelo profile">Harabec Woodwalker</a> (Wood Elf)
<a href="http://www.oboo.org" title="www.OBOO.org" >Bears of Oboo</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/udiako.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Diako</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(5/28/02 10:51:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2494.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kitting, and things Druid need to realize...</span><hr size=1> As I said, I can't complain much about that eitherway.  Using a class to it's full potential is their right.   &quot;But&quot;, they need to know how to use that potention without causing harm to others.<br>
<br>
We're probably talking about 5% of the Druid population that's totally clueless and giving a bad name to the other 95%...   Sad thing, that 5% causes enough damage for a lot to hate all of them.  I have discussions in Guild where I've heard people bitching about them a lot.  Aye, I don't want to be a hypocrite... when I do play a Druid and I get to lvl 34+... I will be Quadding.  I'll try to do it in areas where I don't affect anyone, but that's not always sure.  One thing is for sure, even though I might goof.  I know that if I kite something, and there's people around... I have to be extra carefull not to get anyone hurt or killed.  And If I do have an oops, it's my responsability to first Apologize, and 2nd try to fix it if I can..  Running/logging/moving is a coward way of acting.<br>
<br>
Again...  The topic here isn't about Druid hogging the mobs.  It's about some Druids not knowing that if they aren't carefull, their pulls could end up killing someone else in their path.  And NO, it's not their fault most of those times. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub110.ezboard.com/udiako.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Diako</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(5/28/02 10:54:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub110.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2494.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Kitting, and things Druid need to realize...</span><hr size=1> Bah... 2nd post I make, where I see typo's all over the place... and I can't edit.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
