<br>
Lower level druids:  Before you start quad-kiting on your own, go find and watch a higher-level druid who knows what they are doing.  (As a grouping Druid, I am just really learning solo quad-kiting myself.) Quad kiting can be very different from regular kiting because you are not rooting the mob and using dot, you are snaring and grouping your mobs as close together as possible so you can use the aoe spells on them.  This involves LOTS of running around and it's easy to accidentally train others.  Also, start out on mobs that are indifferent - they don't automatically aggro unless you hit them (elephants, mammoth's, rhino's, etc...).  That way if you do accidentally run past others, no one gets hurt.<br>
<br>
Quad-kiting Druids:  Our SOW (and wolf-form) gets faster as we go up in level so if you don't take that into consideration, you can outrun your mobs.  Also, if there is a mistake and someone does get trained, APOLOGIZE, DAMMIT!   Be helpful and heal them or find them a rez if they died.<br>
<br>
